"Blackrod, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Calais, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Calais, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Bradshagh was born in 1378, in Blackrod, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh Bradshaw, was 23 and his mother, Margaret de Verdun 2nd Baroness de Verdun, was 27. He married Lady Johanna Blackrod Bradshagh about 1400. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1415, in Westleigh, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1378–1415":"1378–1415","1381–1436":"1381–1436","1403–1480":"1403–1480","1405–1429":"1405–1429","1355–1383":"1355–1383","1351–1436":"1351–1436","1351":"1351","1383":"1383","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","1480":"1480","1381":"1381","1415":"1415","1403":"1403","1436":"1436","1378":"1378","1377":"1377","1355":"1355","28 August 1383":"28. august 1383","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Blackrod, Lancashire, England":"Blackrod, Lancashire, England","Blackrod, Greater Manchester, England, United Kingdom":"Greater Manchester, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Westleigh, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Westleigh, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blackrod Lanc